Only alteration is the front sight has been field-adjusted for accuracy. Barrel length is 2 ½”, round butt grip, pinned and recessed barrel, and adjustable rear sights. Overall a very nice revolver. Get a free Hunter brand leather holster with Buy-It-Now! 



The Model 19 was produced in blued carbon steel or nickel-plated steel with wood or rubber combat grips, an adjustable rear sight, semi-target hammer, serrated combat-type trigger, and was available in 2.5" (3": Model 66—rare), 4", or 6-inch barrel lengths. The weights are 30.5 ounces, 36 ounces, and 39 ounces, respectively. The 2.5- and 3-inch barrel versions had a round butts, while the others had square butts. 

The Model 19 was produced from 1957 (first model number stampings) to November 1999. The Model 66 was produced from 1970 until 2005. The Model 66 differed by its use of stainless steel and its smooth target-type trigger. The Model 19 and the Model 66 had the same trigger options. 

Engineering changes were designated with a "dash-" number after the model number. The engineering changes are as follows: 

•	19 (1957): Stamping of model number. 
•	19-1 (1959): Change extractor rod, right to left-hand thread. 
•	19-2 (1961): Cylinder stop changed, delete trigger-guard screw. 
o	(1963): Introduce 6" barrel. 
o	(1963): 50 manufactured with 2.5" barrel, serial range K544672–K544721. 
o	(1966): Introduce 2.5" barrel as standard. 
•	19-3 (1967): Relocation of rear sight leaf screw.

title: For Sale:  Norinco JW-14 Semi- Auto. 22LR
location: Traverse City, Northern Lower Peninsula, Michigan
postcontent:
This is a Norinco JW-14 semi auto rifle chambered in the. 22LR round. This is a very nice shooting rifle that is modeled after the famous M1 in design. With a ramped rear sight and a grooved receiver, you can use the vintage style iron sights and do some plinking, or pop on a 3x9x40 scope and you are ready for some small game action! Includes (2) 7 round mags, approximately 500 rounds of ammo, and a brown soft gun case for free. I have ran approximately 750 rounds through this rifle, and it shoots very straight indeed! These rifles are no longer legal to import to the US because of a ban on them for some reason or another. The most famous Norinco product is their version of the SKS. In the .22LR, the bolt action JW-15 is fairly easy to come by, however finding the semi-auto version is quite rare. 

This gun shoots great, and I have taught my son to shoot on this rifle. The only small quirks that it does have is that sometimes the semi auto action will not catch the trigger when it cycles. This is remedied by slightly moving the trigger forward in between rounds so that it catches on the action. Also, the safety does not function. This is because the safety slide is held in place by the upper portion of the aluminum trigger group. There is a small piece of aluminium  that is broke off. I'm sure a gunsmith could repair this. However, I have not fixed it because I have always been taught to treat every gun as if it were loaded, and I have taught that same safety to my children.

I have priced this rifle in accordance to what I feel this gun is worth. However, I am open to offers, both on the price and on a trade. I am currently in the market for a 17HMR rifle or a semi auto pistol chambered in a .22LR. If you have something I'm looking for, I am willing to do a trade with cash as well.

Asking $125 or best offer.


Thanks for looking.

Josh
